courses.description: Selected Topics Repeatable with departmental consent.

Financial Accounting The study of accounting as a means of communicating financial information about the activities of business enterprises. Emphasizes concepts and principles underlying the measurement of income and financial position and how this information may be used to evaluate the progress of a firm.

Managerial Accounting The study of accounting in terms of management's information requirements. Emphasizes the use of accounting information to assist management in planning, analyzing, and implementing business decisions and activities. Prerequisite: ACCT 210.

ACCT 310. Financial Accounting and Reporting: Assets An in-depth study of the conceptual and technical aspects of financial accounting. Emphasizes recognition and measurement problems of income determination and balance sheet presentation. Covers asset accounting in depth. Prerequisites: completion of ACCT 210 and BADM 160 with a grade of C (2.000) or better, advanced standing, junior standing.

Accounting for Decision Making and Control The use of accounting information to assist management in planning, analyzing, and implementing processes for decision making and control. Focus is operational control in contemporary business contexts. Prerequisites: completion of ACCT 220 and 260 with a grade of C or better, advanced standing, junior standing.
Special Group Studies in Business Repeatable for credit with School of Accountancy consent. Prerequisites: junior standing, advanced standing.

Financial Accounting and Reporting: Equities A continuation of ACCT 310. Emphasizes liabilities and equity. Prerequisites: completion of ACCT 310 with a grade of C or better, advanced standing, junior standing.

Introduction to Federal Income Tax An overview of the federal tax law and those laws specifically applicable to individuals and sole proprietors. Also introduces tax research techniques. Prerequisites: completion of ACCT 310 with a grade of C or better, advanced standing, junior standing.
